  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through various mechanisms and frameworks:\n\n1. Global Standard-Setting Bodies\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) establishes international standards\n- Provides recommendations that countries implement into national legislation\n- Creates mutual evaluation processes to assess legal compliance\n\n2. Treaty Frameworks\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Palermo Convention\n- Vienna Convention\n- These treaties require signatory nations to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. Legal Harmonization\n- Countries develop similar legal definitions and approaches\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Consistent due diligence protocols for financial institutions\n\n4. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Mechanisms for cross-border investigations\n- Information sharing between national law enforcement agencies\n- Extradition provisions for money laundering prosecutions\n\n5. Regulatory Compliance\n- Banks must implement international anti-money laundering (AML) protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting requirements\n\n6. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International cooperation in tracking financial transactions\n- Sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Coordinated efforts to disrupt money laundering networks\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating financial crimes globally.",
